Immediately Nextflow is a little weird, and the documentation doesn't seem quite as beginner friendly. They do a decent job saying
how to do something, but they haven't explained the concepts well from the get go.
Nextflow is a good bit more intuitive than Snakemake, and I think a large part of my confusion is coming from not knowing Groovy.
Although they do tend to simply introduce stuff without explaining it a good amount.
They have a set of pipelines called nf-core! https://nf-co.re/
Wow Nextflow is annoying as heck. Installation sux, java sux, nf-core keeps failing, looking at logs is incomprehensible, no large
groovy community that has run into many issues and can help you, groovy documentation is annoying as heck need to literally learn
all that language.
The -resume option seems to have worked and feels nice :)
I ran into several issues: first off STAR doesn't work on my computer because I run out of memory and stuff just fails. Then I tried it on
the servers, but docker wouldn't work so I needed singulairity. With singulairity I ran into issues where the images would not get
pulled down randomly. The workflow would occaisonally work, but inconsistent which was worrysome. I don't actually know if it was

Tutorial link: https://www.nextflow.io/docs/latest/getstarted.html
My first script:
Well first off this is a pretty disorienting start. They give me a script and I don't fully understand the
layout. Turns out parallel processes don't run in the same order, so different resutls can print before
others.
Very nice feature is that Nextflow immediately produces logs, no need for the user to make them,
although they are a bit incomprehensible.
It creates a weird work file that I simply do not understand.
Modify and resume:
Huge quality of life improvement over Snakemake: if a piece of script is changed, that portion alone
is re-run. No weird work around is needed like for Snakemake.
Just need to rerun the command with "nextflow run tutorial.nf -resume"
KEY: Cached information is stored in ./work directory. This may take up a lot of space, so if I don't
plan to resume the pipeline, clean out this folder.
Pipeline parameters:
They don't really describe what a pipeline parameter is, but we can make one simply by having the
prefix "params.NAME". The value of the parameter can be specified at the commandline with --
NAME.
Basic concepts:
Process and channels:
Nextflow ties together a bunch of scripting languages that can be executed on linux.
Process=task
Channel=asynchronous queue (outputs go into channels?)
Links are not established based on naming schemes! They are based on whether a channel is
defined in the input or the output.
Execution abstraction:
Process defines what a command has to execute, the executor determines how the script is run. By
default the executor is the local computer.
Configuration options:
Define properties in the .config file which should live in the same directory. Here we can define
which executor to use "Cloud, HPC, Job scheduler, local" and any local process environment
variables.
Groovy Language Basics:
Looks like in the .nf file, you can just type a Groovy syntaxed command and it will run as if it were its own stand
alone language.
Note editing the script in anyway reruns other processes it looks like
Lists and dictionaries look similar to python, although they call dict maps.
If/else is done with
if (x < 0.5) {
}
Else {
Println "You won!"
}
Within quotes you can access variables with $foxtype ${foxcolor.join()} can run an expression. Without quotes
just foxtype or baseDir will do.
Like on bash using the \ inside of a multiline string will negate the \n
Within a process {} the "task" keyword can let you access variables you have defined.
You can make a type of generator (python) using curly braces when defining a variable.
This honestly feels like a lambda maybe?
"square = { it * it }"
Not super interesting until it is connected to other functions to string along stuff.
[1,2,3,4].collect(square)
This says make the array, and run square on each element, collecting them in another array.
Can have multiple variables not just "it".
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2993462/groovy-what-does-
mean This post describes what the -> operator does.
Basic read/write:
Create a file variable using file(/path/to/file/or/directory). Then we can see the contents of the file with myFile.text
operation.
We can append to the file using myFile.append("add this line\n") or myFile << "add a line more\n".
Reading line by line:
Similar to python
allLines = myFile.readLines()
For (line : allLines){stuff}
Reading line by line for big files we can use eachLine. eachLine makes use of the closure stuff we learned
earlier so it might take some getting used to.
Extensive file and directory movement: https://www.nextflow.io/docs/latest/script.html#list-directory-content
Processes:
Super basic process definition:
Needs the keyword process, a name, and curly braces. Inside the curlies we need at least one bit of executable
script.
Processes structure:
We can have 5 elements in a process. Except my script doesn't seem to work :(
Wow that was annoying. So the base output of a bash script goes into the work/ directory and within that
into other weird subdirectories??? To get the file to write to my baseDir I had to do a little work around:
The single quotes around the variable expansion are important for me because my directory path has
spaces, causing Bash to freak out. This way the stuff expands inside of them, but the linux knows that it is
all one unit.
Scripting:
We can use different languages by specifying with a shebang what language we intend the script portion
to be executed in.

To generalize the above code to most if not all systems, use #!/user/bin/env python
Conditional scripts:
https://www.nextflow.io/docs/latest/process.html#scripts-a-la-carte
We can make the script and if() else if() else() by prefixing the '''''' with "script:"
Template modularization:
We can put a script to be executed into a template/ directory where the .nf file is, and reference it from a
process via
We also have the shell directive:
https://www.nextflow.io/docs/latest/process.html#shellwhich lets us use
scripts similar to script, but lets us use both nextflow variables and bash variables.
Native execution:
https://www.nextflow.io/docs/latest/process.html#native-execution
We can have something execute natively without the shell using the exec: command and some groovy
language.
Inputs:
https://www.nextflow.io/docs/latest/process.html#inputs
Processes are somewhat isolated but can send over values through channels.
Rules: Only one input block per channel, and it must have one or more input declarations?
Syntax:
Qualifier is the type of data
□
If the input name is the same as the channel name, then the from … part can be omited and it looks like
this:
Pretty neat functionality, but if you have a bunch of files in a directory, but want them to end up
having the same name, you can do "file "fastafile" from proteins" and if you echo it, it will look
like fastafile1 fastafile2 …
□
So to summarize:
If we have a channel, we can put the list into a variable using from, and access it from the
commandline command using ${query_file}. If the variable name will be the same as the channel
name we can just do file proteins and access it using $proteins. If wawant to have all the channel
list stuff have the same name, we name it 'query.fa' and access it just as query.fa. If we use a
wildcard the 'query*.fa' will transform into 'query1.fa' 'query2.fa' etc.


the server. No clue how to impose a global limit.

I haven't even gotten to containerization yet

A test set may not be exhaustive, so when you get to the end of the program, something might
error. If a tool errors, you can generally fix it and click resume, but if it was an issue with the
pipeline itself, you are SOL, fix the script, rerun it. Building pipelines on our own without
consulting someone that knows nextflow or groovy well may be incredibly tedious and difficult.

are the same.
